    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Clinus fucorum, Pavoclinus fucorum.</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_3505",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Klipfishes of the family Clinidae are small, elongate, laterally-compressed, bottom-dwelling fishes with a single dorsal fin stretching head to tail. The pelvic fin is inserted in front of the pectoral fin and consists of just 2–3 elongate rays (and one concealed spine) and the tail is rounded. All species are viviparous and the males have a prominent intromittent organ just behind the anus. The group is particularly common and diverse in intertidal and shallow water systems along the southern and western coasts of South Africa and together these make up the continent’s largest group of endemic fish species.</p><p>This species has a characteristic body shape, being very laterally compressed with a short, steeply inclined head. The tall dorsal fin originates far forwards, almost above the eyes, and is expanded anteriorly into a large, rounded crest formed by the first five spines, but with no notch in the membrane behind this crest. The dorsal fine has 28–31 spines and 4–6 rays. Body colour fairly uniform green, yellow or dark brown, often pale patches on fins and a white patch beneath base of pectoral fin.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_3506",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Up to at least 20 cm total length, some sources report 30 cm.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_3507",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> False Bay to Eastern Cape.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_3508",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>A rare species usually associated with kelps and other algae. No other details known.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_3509",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Diet of this species has not been studied, but the cryptic colouration and apparent sluggish habits suggest it is an ambush predator of invertebrates.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_3510",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Species-specific details unknown, but all clinids are livebearers, males copulating with females and fertilizing the eggs internally with their intromittent organs. Juveniles develop inside the females’ ovaries and in most species the live young are born in spring, have a short planktonic life then settle on the bottom.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_3511",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>The laterally compressed body, blunt steeply-sloping head, and large crest on the dorsal fin readily identify this species.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_3512",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Heemstra, P, Heemstra, E, Ebert, D, Holleman, W & Randall, J (2022). Coastal Fishes of the Western Indian Ocean. National Research Foundation & South African Institute for Aquatic Biodiversity, South Africa. Volume 4 (p. 404). <br><br>Smith, MM & Heemstra, P (eds.) (2003). Smith's Sea Fishes. Struik Publishers, Cape Town (p. 768).<br><br>Zsilavecz, G (2005). Coastal Fishes of the Cape Peninsula and False Bay. SURG, Cape Town (p. 68).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_3513",
